          "title": "The hired Levite — credential without calling",
          "body": "The Levite's entrance in verses 7-9 initially appears to offer a correction. If anyone knows how YHWH's worship should be ordered, it is a Levite. But the narrator immediately undermines the expectation: this Levite has no destination, no assignment, and no post. He has been residing in Bethlehem — a non-Levitical city — and he departs for 'wherever he might find a place' (17:8). When Micah offers him a salary of ten shekels per year, a suit of clothes, and provisions (17:10), the Levite agrees (*yaal*, 17:11) — a word that emphasizes willingness. He is not recruited under duress; he chooses the arrangement. He then allows Micah to 'fill his hand' — to perform the ordination rite that no layman has authority to perform — and says nothing. The Levite's tribal identity, far from legitimating the shrine, makes the corruption worse. He is the person appointed by God to guard the covenant's worship order; he becomes its instrument of corruption. Peter Craigie and Daniel Block (NICOT, Judges) both note that the Levite's behavior in chapter 17 is the religious establishment's failure made personal: the very custodians of covenant worship are the ones most willing to trade their calling for a salary."
